Table 1 lists the expressions for deterioration Dc which characterize the reduction of a certain characteristic of the material after a number of n loading cycles, or increase of specific energy (energy density) irreversibly dissipated with the increase of loading cycles. Table 1.
Deterioration under cyclic loading, Dc, as measure of the variation of a certain material characteristic.
Nr. Deterioration by: Relation Observations
1. Reduced rigidity: Dc=1-E(n)E0
Fitzgerard and Wang (Kaminski, 2002);
E(n) – elasticity module after n loading cycles;
E0 – elasticity module of undamaged material.
2. Reduced fatigue strength: Dc=1-σR(n)σu(0)
Henry (Hansen, 1999; Kaminski, 2002);
σR(n) – fatigue strength with an asymmetrical cycle R after n loading cycles;
σu(0) – ultimate stress of undamaged material (n=0).
3. Increased irreversibly dissipated specific energy: Dc=Eir(n)Et(n)
Jinescu (1993); Shang and Yao (1999);
Eir(n) – irreversibly dissipated specific energy throughout n cycles loading;
Et – total specific energy acumulated up to failure (n).

Table 2 sums up the relations provided by literature in the field of determining the deterioration calculated on the basis of the accumulation of deformations or number of loading cycles. Out of the relations proposed for D the most used is the Palmgren–Miner relation (position 3 in Table 2), which however does not take into consideration the behavior of the material (linear or nonlinear). The most important limits of Palmgren–Miner's rule are in considering a linear accumulation of damage ignoring the load sequences and the impossibility to take into account the loading background (Bagmutov and Savkin, 2007). Table 2.
Deterioration through cyclic loading, D, as a measure of partial accumulation through total strain up to failure or the total number of loading cycles.
Nr. Deterioration through accumulationof Relation Observations
1. Strain: D=ɛ(n)ɛ(N)
Hwang and Han (Hwang and Han, 1986; Kaminski, 2002);
ɛ(n), ɛ(N) strain after n loading cycles and N failure cycles, respectively.
2. D=A·∫0n(ɛ(n)ɛ(N))m·dn
Hansen (Hwang and Han, 1986; Kaminski, 2002);
A and m – material constants.
3. A certain number of loading: Cycles: D=nN
Palmgren and Miner (Miner, 1945; Mischke, 1986; Tateishi et al., 2007);
n; N – number of loading cycles with stress amplitude, σa; effective number of loading cycles, respectively up to failure.
4. D=nN·(σaσa,max)a
Morrow (Morrow, 1986; Kaminski, 2002);
σa,max – maximum σa value throughout loading;
a – exponent (for stainless steel of 304 type a=-0.5) (Chen et al., 2006).
5. D=(nN)p
Marko and Starkey (Chen et al., 2006)
- exponent p has been considered as dependent on the applied stress (Marko and Starkey, 1954), or as independent loading constant (Hwang and Han, 1986; Kaminski, 2002).
6. D=A·(nN)-B·(nN)2
Owen and Howe (Kaminski, 2002);
A and B – constant;
7. D=1-(1-nN)b
Lemaitre and Plumetree (Shang and Yao, 1999);
b – exponent dependent on stress amplitude, σa, mean stress, σm, and fatigue limit, σR.
8. D=1-[1-(nN)1/(1-α)]1/(1+β)
Datoma and collaborators. (Dattoma et al., 2006);
- result obtained on the basis of general relations of Chaboche and Lemaitre (Chaboche, 1981; Lemaitre and Chaboche, 1990);
α, β – constants.

