The problem of effect superposition raises a range of issues. It refers to the total effect produced by the simultaneous or successive loading with one or several loads of the same kind or of different kind. In the case of cyclic thermo-mechanical loading one can identify the following important cases:


– cyclic loading with normal and shear stresses;

– cyclic loading with several successive steps of loading of the same kind, or random loading;

– cyclic loading of a vibrating element;

– cyclic loading in a corroding environment.

The design material of the structure is steel featuring:


– ultimate stress: σu=510 MPa; τu=420 MPa;

– yield stress: σy=390 MPa; τy=300 MPa;

– fatigue limit: σ-1=260 MPa; τ-1=215 MPa;

– number of cycles at the knee point: N0=2×106;

– exponents: α=1.1 and m = 3.

In the most dangerous section of the structure (Buch, 1976; Buzdugan and Blumenfeld, 1979):


– stress concentration factors: Kσ=1.8; Kτ=1.5;

– dimensional coefficient: ɛd=0.8;

– surface quality coefficient: γs=0.9.

The general relations of deteriorating a structure under the action of a single cyclic stress, (16) and (17), are used for the calculation of the deterioration produced by superposition of other loadings over the cyclic loading with normal stresses. Expressions have been obtained for the total deterioration produced to a mechanical structure by:


– cyclic loading of a structure only with normal or only with shear stresses, relations (16) and (17);

– cyclic simultaneous stresses with normal and shear stresses of a sample (21) or of a mechanical structure (23);

– cyclic loading with several normal and shear stress blocks of a sample (25) or of any mechanical structure (26);

– cyclic loading of a structure undergoing vibrations with normal or only shear stresses (28);

– cyclic loading with normal stresses in a corroding environment of a crackless sample (31), and with cracks (32), as well as of a mechanical structure (34) and (35).
